{{Redirect-distinguish|Biomedical science|Biomedical research}} {{see also|Biomedicine}} {{Use dmy dates|date=July 2014}} [[File:Love what you do.jpg|thumb|300x300px|A biochemist engaged in bench research]]
'''Biomedical sciences''' are a set of [[applied science]]s applying portions of [[natural science]] or [[formal science]], or both, to knowledge, interventions, or technology that are of use in [[healthcare]] or [[public health]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Consultations/Liveconsultations/DH_091137?IdcService=GET_FILE&dID=181510&Rendition=Web |title=The Future of the Healthcare Science Workforce. Modernising Scientific Careers: The Next Steps. |page=2 |accessdate=1 June 2011 |date=26 Nov 2008 }}</ref> Such disciplines as [[medical microbiology]], [[clinical virology]], [[clinical epidemiology]], [[genetic epidemiology]], and [[biomedical engineering]] are medical sciences. In explaining [[physiology|physiological]] mechanisms operating in [[pathology|pathological processes]], however, [[pathophysiology]] can be regarded as [[basic science]].
==Roles within biomedical science== There are at least 45 different specialisms within healthcare science, which are traditionally grouped into three main divisions:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/prod_consum_dh/groups/dh_digitalassets/@dh/@en/@ps/documents/digitalasset/dh_117982.pdf |title=Extraordinary You |publisher=Department of Health|page=116 |accessdate=1 June 2011 |date=16 July 2010 }}</ref> * specialisms involving [[life sciences]] * specialisms involving [[Human physiology|physiological science]] * specialisms involving [[medical physics]] or [[bioengineering]]
===Life sciences specialties=== {{cmn|colwidth=30em| * [[Molecular toxicology]] * [[Molecular pathology]] * [[Blood transfusion]] science * Cervical [[Cytopathology|cytology]] * Clinical [[biochemistry]] * Clinical [[embryology]] * Clinical [[immunology]] * [[Electron microscopy]] * External [[quality assurance]] * [[Haematology]] * [[Haemostasis]] and [[thrombosis]] * [[Histocompatibility]] and [[immunogenetics]] * [[Histopathology]] and [[cytopathology]] * [[Molecular genetics]] and [[cytogenetics]] * [[Molecular biology]] and [[cell biology]] * [[Microbiology]] including [[mycology]] * [[Bacteriology]] * [[Tropical diseases]] * [[Phlebotomy]] * [[Tissue bank|Tissue banking]]/[[Organ transplant|transplant]] * [[Virology]] }}
===Physiological science specialisms=== {{cmn|colwidth=30em| * [[Audiology|Audiology and hearing therapy]] * Autonomic neurovascular function * [[Cardiac physiology]] * [[Perfusionist|Clinical perfusion]] * [[Intensive-care medicine|Critical care science]] * [[Gastrointestinal physiology]] * [[Neurophysiology]] * [[Ophthalmology|Ophthalmic]] and [[vision science]] * [[Respiratory physiology|Respiratory and sleep physiology]] * [[Urology]] * [[Vascular disease|Vascular science]] }}
===Physics and bioengineering specialisms=== {{cmn|colwidth=30em| * [[Biomechanical engineering]] * [[Biomedical engineering]] * [[Clinical engineering]] * Clinical measurement * [[Diagnostic radiology]] * Equipment management * [[Facial prosthetics|Maxillofacial prosthetics]] * [[Medical electronics]] * [[Medical engineering]] design * [[Medical illustration|Medical illustration and clinical photography]] * [[Non-ionising radiation]] * [[Nuclear medicine]] * [[Nuclear pharmacy|Radiopharmacy]] * [[Radiation protection]] and monitoring * [[Radiotherapy]] physics * [[Rehabilitation engineering]] * [[Dialysis|Renal technology and science]] * [[Ultrasound]] }}
== Biomedical science in the United Kingdom == The healthcare science workforce is an important part of the UK's [[National Health Service]]. While people working in healthcare science are only 5% of the staff of the NHS, 80% of all diagnoses can be attributed to their work.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publicationsandstatistics/Publications/PublicationsPolicyAndGuidance/DH_113275 |title=Modernising Scientific Careers: The UK Way Forward |page=3 |accessdate=1 June 2011 |date=26 Feb 2010 }}</ref>
The volume of specialist healthcare science work is a significant part of the work of the NHS. Every year, NHS healthcare scientists carry out: * nearly 1 billion pathology laboratory tests * more than 12 million physiological tests * support for 1.5 million [[Radiation therapy|fractions]] of radiotherapy
The four governments of the UK have recognised the importance of healthcare science to the NHS, introducing the [[Modernising Scientific Careers]] initiative to make certain that the education and training for healthcare scientists ensures there is the flexibility to meet patient needs while keeping up to date with scientific developments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dh.gov.uk/en/Publicationsandstatistics/Publications/PublicationsPolicyAndGuidance/DH_113275 |title=Modernising Scientific Careers: The UK Way Forward |page=5 |accessdate=1 June 2011 |date=26 Feb 2010 }}</ref>
